#### 5.3.1 Electronic Effects

Electronic effects influence the distribution of electrons in a particular chemical species and hence its reactivity. They can be electron-withdrawing or electron-donating, depending on the functional groups involved.

The inductive effect arises from the polarisation of electron density in a bond due to the electronegativity of nearby atoms.

Consider chloroeethane, propan-1-ol and ethylamine below. C/, O and N are more electronegative than C, hence they draw electron density away from carbon, resulting in a partial positive charge (6+) on the carbon next to them. This is the inductive effect.

