## 3 Solubility equilibria and solubility product, \(K_{\text{sp}}\)

_10 10.10.2(a): show understanding of, and apply, the concept of solubility product, \(K_{\text{sp}}\)_

When increasing quantities of a sparingly soluble ionic salt are added to water, a saturated solution will eventually be formed. Upon addition of excess solute, a dynamic **equilibrium** is set up, in which there is simultaneous dissolution of the excess undissolved solute and precipitation of the solute from the ions in the solution. These two processes take place at the same rate. Ions in the saturated solution are at equilibrium with the excess undissolved solute:

\[\text{MX(s)}\rightleftharpoons\text{M}^{\ast}\text{(aq)}+X^{\ast}\text{(aq)}\]

Now, consider a mixture containing a saturated aqueous solution of silver chloride and some undissolved silver chloride. The system is at **equilibrium**:

\[\text{AgCl}(s)\rightleftharpoons\text{Ag}^{\ast}\text{(aq)}+Cl(\text{aq)}\]

We can write:

\[\text{HX}_{\text{sp}}\]

However, [AgCl] represents the 'concentration' of a pure solid, and is therefore a constant.

\[\text{Therefore,}\]

\[\text{$K_{\text{sp}}$}\times\text{[AgCl]}=\text{[Ag}^{\ast}][Cl^{\ast}]\]

\[\text{$K_{\text{sp}}$}\Rightarrow\text{[Ag}^{\ast}][Cl^{\ast}]\]

The new constant, \(K_{\text{sp}}\), is called the solubility product of AgCl.

\[\text{Units of $K_{\text{sp}}$}\text{of $AgCl$:mol^{2}\,dm^{-6}}\]

DEFINITION

**Solubility product, \(K_{\text{sp}}\), of a sparingly soluble salt** is the product of the molar concentrations of the constituent ions in a **saturated solution**, raised to the appropriate powers at a given temperature.

_Note_: Appropriate power refers to the stoichiometric coefficient of the substance in the balanced equation for the reaction.

* The concept of solubility product is valid only for sparingly soluble salts. For soluble salts such as NaCl, CuSO\({}_{4}\) and AgNO\({}_{3}\), the use of the \(K_{\text{sp}}\) concept is inappropriate.
* As such, for sparingly soluble salts, the numerical value of \(K_{\text{sp}}\) is always very small, rarely exceeding \(10^{-4}\) and can be as low as \(10^{-40}\).
* Like other equilibrium constants, the value of \(K_{\text{sp}}\) changes only with temperature.

